ğŸ”¹ What is a Router?

A router is a Layer 3 network device that connects different networks together and forwards data packets between them using IP addresses.

Its primary role is to determine the best path for data to travel from a source network to a destination network.

â¸»

ğŸ”¹ Core Functions of a Router

1ï¸âƒ£ Packet Forwarding

Routers examine the destination IP address in a packet and use a routing table to determine where to send it next.

2ï¸âƒ£ Network Address Translation (NAT)

Routers translate private IP addresses (e.g., 192.168.x.x) into a public IP address so multiple devices can share a single internet connection.

Example:
	â€¢	Laptop: 192.168.1.10
	â€¢	Phone: 192.168.1.11
	â€¢	Router public IP: 86.x.x.x

NAT allows both devices to access the internet using one public IP.

3ï¸âƒ£ Default Gateway

In a local network, the router acts as the default gateway.
If a device wants to communicate outside its local network, it sends the traffic to the router.

4ï¸âƒ£ Basic Firewall & Security

Most routers include built-in firewall functionality that:
	â€¢	Blocks unsolicited inbound traffic
	â€¢	Filters traffic based on rules
	â€¢	Helps protect internal devices from external threats

